e from any of thirty or more farmsteads so named, notably in Møre og Romsdal, from Old Norse <i>stokkr</i> ‘log, trunk, beam’, denoting either growing timber or a natural formation shaped like a log, for example a straight-sided inlet. Compare   Stocke  ."]}]},{"name":"Randle","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: medieval vernacular form of   Randolf .  This was in common use as a given name into the 17th century and gave rise to a surname. In modern use the given name is often a transferred use of this surname."],"variants":[{"name":"Randell","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: medieval vernacular form of   Randolf .  This was in common use as a given name into the 17th century and gave rise to a surname. In modern use the given name is often a transferred use of this surname."]},{"name":"Randal","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: medieval vernacular form of   Randolf .  This was in common use as a given name into the 17th century and gave rise to a surname. In modern use the given name is often a transferred use of this surname."]},{"name":"Randel","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: medieval vernacular form of   Randolf .  This was in common use as a given name into the 17th century and gave rise to a surname. In modern use the given name is often a transferred use of this surname."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Randle de Stocke was born about 1280, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. He married Rosa de Minshull about 1305, in Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter."},"et":{"Abt 1280–":"umbes 1280–Surnud","1280–Female":"1280–Surnud","1313–1365":"1313–1365","1317–Female":"1317–Surnud","1280–Male":"1280–Surnud","1313":"1313","about 1305":"umbes 1305","1365":"1365","Abt 1313":"umbes 1313","Abt 1280":"umbes 1280","Abt 1317":"umbes 1317","1280":"1280","1317":"1317","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Stoke, Cheshire, England":"Stoke, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom